    <node id="The Welsh Government is taking several measures to update the &quot;Parenting. Give it time&quot; campaign and improve support for parents, especially in the context of the proposed legislation to prohibit physical punishment of children. They have acknowledged the need for better awareness and understanding of the current law, as evidenced by a survey indicating that over half of the population believes smacking is already illegal. The Government is working on ensuring the public understands the proposed legislation as they move forward with it.&#10;&#10;In addition to updating the &quot;Parenting. Give it time&quot; campaign, which currently goes up to age 7 and focuses on issues like managing mealtime challenges and tantrums, the Welsh Government plans to extend its scope to cover up to 18 years old. This extension recognizes that the issues faced by parents of older children may be different and require tailored advice and support.&#10;&#10;The Government is also conducting a mapping exercise to identify gaps or opportunities for more support, particularly in terms of providing positive alternatives to physical punishment and online resources for parents. They recognize that many parents use various methods, including the internet, to access information and seek help. This mapping exercise will enable them to create targeted interventions and ensure comprehensive support is available for parents throughout Wales.&#10;&#10;Lastly, the Welsh Government encourages universal services provided by local government, health, education, social services, social justice, and the third sector to help support parents and pass on information about positive alternatives to physical punishment. More targeted supports such as Flying Start and Families First also offer help and advice for parents in need." />
    <node id=". It is very well used by parents. But, of course, this legislation will go up to 18 years old, and so the issues may be very different. So, we're already starting to prepare to update that 'Parenting. Give it time' campaign. And then, obviously, there's the universal services that give access to help and to promote positive parenting, delivered by local government, health, education, social services, social justice and the third sector. We will be encouraging all those agencies that provide that universal service to help support parents and to pass on this information. Then, there will be the more targeted supports, such as Flying Start and Families First, which offer help and advice. But what I've done is I've asked the officials to carry out a mapping exercise to see where the support is and where the gaps are or opportunities to do more, particularly around information and advice on positive alternatives to physical punishment, but also more widely. So, we are looking to see where the gaps are. I think parents do tend to use information and try to get help in many different ways. A very large number, actually, do use the internet. I was surprised, actually, that so many used the internet to get information. Others ask their mothers, their" />
