    <edge source="Your question asks for an assessment of the various statistics on the relationship between banning corporal punishment and child-on-child violence, specifically in comparison to a recent study of 88 countries that found an association between prohibiting corporal punishment and less youth violence.&#10;&#10;Based on the meeting transcript provided, there is debate surrounding the interpretation of different statistics from Sweden regarding whether child-on-child violence increased following the ban on physical punishment. The methodological ways of interpreting these statistics make it difficult to establish causation. However, a recent study of 88 countries concluded that if a country prohibits corporal punishment, there is an association with less youth violence. This is one of the largest cross-national analyses of youth violence, with over 400,000 participants. Therefore, while there may be conflicting statistics on this issue, there is also evidence suggesting that banning corporal punishment is associated with lower levels of youth violence." target="1. The purpose of the proposed Bill is to prohibit all forms of physical punishment against children, with the aim of protecting children's rights and ensuring that they have the same protection from physical punishment as adults. This change removes the legal defense for reasonable chastisement, which currently allows parents to use physical punishment as a form of discipline.&#10;2. According to a written consultation, nearly 70 percent of individuals who responded in a personal capacity do not support this Bill. Parents have expressed their understanding of the difference between child abuse and a light smack from a loving parent, indicating that they may perceive the proposed ban as an infringement on their ability to discipline their children.">
