    <edge source="Your question asks for an assessment of the various statistics on the relationship between banning corporal punishment and child-on-child violence, specifically in comparison to a recent study of 88 countries that found an association between prohibiting corporal punishment and less youth violence.&#10;&#10;Based on the meeting transcript provided, there is debate surrounding the interpretation of different statistics from Sweden regarding whether child-on-child violence increased following the ban on physical punishment. The methodological ways of interpreting these statistics make it difficult to establish causation. However, a recent study of 88 countries concluded that if a country prohibits corporal punishment, there is an association with less youth violence. This is one of the largest cross-national analyses of youth violence, with over 400,000 participants. Therefore, while there may be conflicting statistics on this issue, there is also evidence suggesting that banning corporal punishment is associated with lower levels of youth violence." target="The text suggests that there is no expectation for the enactment of the Bill to lower the threshold for significant harm or change child protection procedures. The proposed legislation aims to prohibit all forms of physical punishment against children and ensure that they have the same protection from physical punishment as adults, removing the legal defense for reasonable chastisement. While there may be an initial surge in reported incidents, social services professionals believe that awareness-raising campaigns and ongoing support for parents will lead to a decrease in physical punishment incidents over time. The British Association of Social Workers supports the legislation but emphasizes the importance of working closely with social services and collecting relevant data to monitor changes after the Bill's implementation. Overall, while there may be potential workload increases, professionals are prepared and believe they have adequate resources to support the Bill's implementation without lowering the threshold for significant harm or changing child protection procedures significantly.">
