    <edge source=" parents to decide how best to punish their children, including the use of physical punishment. That is used as an argument by those who are opposed to stopping physical punishment. But these rights are not absolute, and action can therefore be taken that interferes with them, provided the interference is justified. It's the Government's view that the Bill's provisions are necessary in order to protect the rights and freedom of children. We are looking here from the point of view of children. The Bill's provisions are regarded as proportionate measures, and given the fundamental importance of protecting children from inhumane or degrading punishment or other ill treatment, we do consider that we have balanced the rights in a proportionate way. And then, article 10, freedom of expression, and article 14, prohibition of discrimination—these rights are not absolute and action can be taken, therefore, that interferes with them, providing the interference is justified. We don't think it's clear that article 10 and 14 rights are being interfered with, but even if they are, we consider we can justify the interference in order to protect the rights and freedoms of children. I don't know, Emma, whether you wanted to add anything to any of that.&#10;Speaker: Emma Gammon&#10;Content: Only that" target="The speakers, Hefin David AM and Julie Morgan AM, discussed the assessments made in preparation for the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill regarding the balance of relevant articles of the European Convention on Human Rights. These articles include:&#10;&#10;1. Article 3 - Prohibition of torture: The Bill ensures that children are protected from physical punishment, which aligns with the requirement of article 3. It also enforces positive obligations on states to protect individuals from ill-treatment or punishment contrary to article 3.&#10;2. Article 8 - Right to respect for private and family life: Opponents of the Bill argue that articles 8 and 9 (freedom of thought, conscience, and religion) protect parents' right to decide how to punish their children, including physical punishment. However, these rights are not absolute and can be limited if the restriction is justified. The government believes that the Bill's provisions are necessary to protect the rights and freedoms of children, and they consider the interference justifiable to protect children from inhumane or degrading treatment.&#10;2. Article 10 - Freedom of expression and article 14 - Prohibition of discrimination: Similar to articles 8 and 9, these rights are not absolute, and action can be taken if it is justified. The speakers do not think that the Bill interferes with these rights, but even if it does, they believe that the interference can be justified to protect children's rights and freedoms.&#10;&#10;In summary, assessments have been made to balance the relevant articles of the European Convention on Human Rights, including articles 3, 8, 9, 10, and 14, in preparation for the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill. The Bill aims to protect children's rights and freedoms while ensuring that any interference with other human rights is justified.">
