    <edge source=", is it not? But what it does is  provide a useful discussion on what good parenting is and what discipline methods are the most effective—that is, discipline methods that parents can use rather than physical punishment. Do you think, therefore, that there's a need to invest much more in programmes to do with parenting and in support services for families in terms of parenting, and that as part of an early intervention strategy that's more co-ordinated and robust than what we have at present?&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Well, we are developing the Bill as part of a much wider package of support for children and their parents, which, of course, is already in place. This obviously includes the 'Parenting. Give it time' campaign, which aims to help parents do the best job that they can by providing positive tips on parenting and information. And we're already preparing now to update that, because, of course, that only goes up to age 7 and deals with issues about how you cope with your kids if they're difficult at meal times and if they have tantrums. It is very well used by parents. But, of course, this legislation will go up to 18 years old, and so the issues may be very different" target="1. Dawn Bowden AM and Julie Morgan AM express concerns about the rise in looked-after children and the potential impact on the workload and resources of those working with them. They mention that this issue was discussed in several sessions with the police and other relevant parties.&#10;2. Hefin David AM asks for a rough estimate of the additional costs that might be associated with the implementation of the Bill, as it could potentially lead to increased referrals and an increased workload for social services, family courts, CAFCASS Cymru, the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), and organizations involved in child safeguarding.&#10;3. Lynne Neagle AM clarifies that CAFCASS did not appear before the committee but rather submitted a letter. Suzy Davies AM wonders about the potential sources of increased reporting under the new Bill, questioning whether it will be primarily from members of the public or professionals.&#10;4. Julie Morgan AM reiterates that there might be an initial increase in reporting of incidents to social services and other organizations but expresses confidence in the successful implementation of the Bill, citing extensive preparation by relevant agencies and the establishment of four work streams to address various aspects of the legislation's impact. She emphasizes the importance of investing in parenting programs and support services as part of a broader early intervention strategy.">
