    <edge source="'re going to consider. Incredible Years—I know it's very successful; I am aware of that programme. I think there are patches all over Wales of really good progress, but, certainly, I'm sure we need to give more support to parents in the early years, and I think they're only too glad to have it as well. Children are very receptive at that age and early intervention is the key to many of the issues that we have to deal with later on.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. We're going to return to some of the parenting issues later, but in the meantime we've got questions from Hefin David.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: Just to take it on the next step from what Siân Gwenllian was asking about—in schools, are teachers ready for this legislation?&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: On our implementation group, the education sector is represented. They've come to the first meeting of the implementation group. So, they're going to be fully involved in the preparation. Obviously, corporal punishment was banned in schools a long time" target="Based on the meeting transcript, it appears that teachers are expected to be prepared for the new legislation regarding parenting issues through various means. The implementation group, which includes representatives from the education sector, is tasked with preparing for the legislation's implementation and ensuring that professionals such as teachers are informed and ready. It is mentioned that teachers may undergo training as part of their in-service training days or courses to incorporate this new legislation into their knowledge and decision-making processes. The education sector's support for the move to ban physical punishment is also noted, implying a general readiness from teachers to adapt to the change. However, there is no explicit discussion about the extent of preparation or resources allocated specifically for teacher training in the transcript.&#10;&#10;It is important to note that while the education sector is represented in the implementation group, it does not necessarily mean that every individual teacher is prepared or involved in the process. The preparation and awareness campaign's success will likely depend on how effectively the information and training are cascaded down to all teachers and school staff. Additionally, there may be a transition period during which teachers become more comfortable with the new legislation and its implications for their professional responsibilities.">
