    <edge source=" work and to look at the implications of it. I'd just like to say how grateful I am for all those organisations giving their time and commitment. They've set up four work streams, looking at parenting advice and support; data collection, evaluation and monitoring; operations, procedures and processes; and out-of-court disposals and diversions. These groups will be taking forward this work and will be looking at many of those issues that you've mentioned, and will also be updated on the progress of the awareness strategy that we will be bringing in. I'm really confident that the legislation will be implemented in a very practical and workable way, because we do have the commitment of all these agencies, and there's been a huge amount of preparation done in the Welsh Government to prepare for this in a way that, I have to say, hasn't been done in some of the other countries—as I mentioned, in Ireland. So, as much preparation as could be done is being done and has been done, but we really now see that the implementation group is taking forward all these issues, and obviously those agencies that are taking part in the implementation group are, on the whole, in support of the principles of this Bill.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;" target="1. The Welsh government has established an implementation group to address issues related to a proposed Bill that aims to prohibit physical punishment of children. This group had its first meeting on May 14th and includes representatives from various organizations such as the police, Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), Association of Directors of Social Services Cymru, Association of Directors of Education in Wales, Welsh Local Government Association, legal profession, and third sector.&#10;2. These organizations have expressed support for the principles of the Bill and are committed to making it work. They have set up four work streams to look at parenting advice and support, data collection, evaluation and monitoring, operations, procedures and processes, and out-of-court disposals and diversions.&#10;3. The implementation group's establishment is part of a broader early intervention strategy that involves investing in parenting programs and support services to mitigate potential workload increases associated with the Bill. No specific financial commitment has been provided upfront by the Welsh government, but they are relying on estimates and preparations made by the involved organizations.&#10;4. The Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services has stated that there is no expectation of significant increases in workload or negative impacts based on their understanding from people running these organizations. The organizations involved are already dealing with child protection and physical punishment issues, so it is not anticipated to be a completely new category of work for them.&#10;5. There have been concerns expressed about the rise in looked-after children and potential impacts on workload and resources for those working with them. There has also been a request for rough estimates of additional costs associated with implementing the Bill, as it could potentially lead to increased referrals and an increased workload for social services, family courts, CAFCASS Cymru, CPS, and organizations involved in child safeguarding.">
