    <edge source="&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Chair.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. Just before Suzy comes in with a supplementary—CAFCASS didn't come to the committee, they've submitted—&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: They sent a letter—that's right. Yes, sorry about that.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Suzy.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Just very quickly, because I don't want to spend a lot of time on this: isn't it going to be true that any increase in workload for social services or schools or whoever is going to depend on reporting rising? Where do you see the likely rise in reporting taking place? Will it be members of the public or is it going to be professionals who feel that this is something that they can't ignore from now on?&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: well, I think it would be mixed. I don't have any view or where it particularly would come from, because if there are any reports that go into agencies now about children being physically punished in any way—I think they investigate those already now. But" target="Based on the meeting transcript, it is expected that there may be a small rise in reports of physical punishment against children following the implementation of the ban. However, the specific source of these reports is not explicitly discussed in the transcript. Julie Morgan AM speculates that reports could come from both members of the public who are made more aware by the legislation, as well as professionals such as school staff who are required to report any instances of physical punishment. Therefore, it is likely that the expected rise in reporting would be driven by a combination of increased public awareness and vigilance, as well as heightened responsibilities for professionals to report suspected cases of physical punishment.">
