orkers supports the legislation but emphasizes the importance of working closely with social services and collecting relevant data to monitor changes after the Bill's implementation.&#10;5. Professionals, including those from CAFCASS and social services, have expressed confidence in their ability to cope with any potential workload increase. They note that physical punishment cases are already being handled by these organizations as part of their regular duties.&#10;6. While there might be some pressure on public services, the legislative area is considered to be a continuation of existing work rather than a new category.&#10;&#10;Based on this information, social services do not anticipate a significant change in intervention thresholds if they receive more reports about instances of physical punishment towards children following the possible change in law. They are prepared for potential workload increases and believe that existing resources can manage any additional referrals. Social work professionals also expect awareness-raising campaigns to lead to a decrease in physical punishment incidents over time.">
