    <edge source="1. The papers noted by the committee include:&#10;   - A letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services providing additional information following an evidence session on May 2nd for the Bill.&#10;   - A response letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services addressing the committee's request for information on CAFCASS Cymru's response to specific points of interest related to the Bill.&#10;   - A letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services informing the committee about research concerning public attitudes towards physical punishment.&#10;2. Suzy Davies AM mentioned the difficulty in differentiating evidence of smacking as isolated incidents from smacking as part of a larger pattern of behavior, emphasizing this challenge during discussions on the Bill." target="1. The purpose of the proposed Bill is to prohibit all forms of physical punishment against children, with the aim of protecting children's rights and ensuring that they have the same protection from physical punishment as adults. This change removes the legal defense for reasonable chastisement, which currently allows parents to use physical punishment as a form of discipline.&#10;2. According to a written consultation, nearly 70 percent of individuals who responded in a personal capacity do not support this Bill. Parents have expressed their understanding of the difference between child abuse and a light smack from a loving parent, indicating that they may perceive the proposed ban as an infringement on their ability to discipline their children.">
