    <edge source="1. The papers noted by the committee include:&#10;   - A letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services providing additional information following an evidence session on May 2nd for the Bill.&#10;   - A response letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services addressing the committee's request for information on CAFCASS Cymru's response to specific points of interest related to the Bill.&#10;   - A letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services informing the committee about research concerning public attitudes towards physical punishment.&#10;2. Suzy Davies AM mentioned the difficulty in differentiating evidence of smacking as isolated incidents from smacking as part of a larger pattern of behavior, emphasizing this challenge during discussions on the Bill." target="Julie Morgan AM, in response to the claim made by Equal Protection Network Cymru, asserts that the Bill aims to protect children's rights and ensure children have the same protection from physical punishment as adults. She acknowledges the varying views on this matter but emphasizes that the Wales Centre for Public Policy's independent literature review found all physical punishment under any conditions to be potentially harmful to children, with no peer-reviewed research suggesting physically punishing a child improves outcomes. While she understands Equal Protection Network Cymru's concerns, she maintains that the committee is reporting the evidence they received from their commissioned research.">
