    <edge source="1. The papers noted by the committee include:&#10;   - A letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services providing additional information following an evidence session on May 2nd for the Bill.&#10;   - A response letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services addressing the committee's request for information on CAFCASS Cymru's response to specific points of interest related to the Bill.&#10;   - A letter from the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services informing the committee about research concerning public attitudes towards physical punishment.&#10;2. Suzy Davies AM mentioned the difficulty in differentiating evidence of smacking as isolated incidents from smacking as part of a larger pattern of behavior, emphasizing this challenge during discussions on the Bill." target="1. The Welsh Government is addressing the challenge of informing the public about the proposed legislation on physical punishment of children by acknowledging the need for better awareness and understanding of the current law. The survey results indicate that over half of the population believes smacking is already illegal, which suggests a misunderstanding. The Welsh Government recognizes this issue and will work towards ensuring that the public understands the proposed legislation as they move forward with it.">
