    <edge source="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee this morning. I have received apologies for absence from Jack Sargeant, and I'm very pleased to welcome Vikki Howells, who is substituting for Jack this morning. Can I ask whether there are any declarations of interest from Members, please? No. Okay. Thank you. Item 2 this morning is our last evidence session on the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill, and I'm really pleased to welcome back Julie Morgan AM, Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services; Karen Cornish, who is deputy director of the children and families division; and Emma Gammon, who is the lawyer working on the Bill. So, thank you all for coming. If you're happy, we'll go straight into questions because we've got lots of ground that we want to cover, and the first questions are from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Good morning. Thank you, Chair. Good morning, Deputy Minister. Of those individuals who responded to our written consultation in a personal capacity, nearly 70 per cent do not support this Bill" target="1. The Welsh government is not providing a specific financial commitment upfront to address potential increased workloads for various agencies, such as social services, family courts, CAFCASS Cymru, and the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS). Instead, they are relying on estimates and preparations made by these organizations.&#10;2. The Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services has stated that, based on their understanding from the people running these organizations, there is no expectation of significant increases in workload or negative impacts.&#10;3. Organizations like CAFCASS, CPS, social services, and others are already dealing with issues related to child protection and physical punishment. Therefore, it is not anticipated to be a completely new category of work for them, but rather an extension or adjustment of their current responsibilities.&#10;4. It remains important to invest in parenting programs and support services as part of a broader early intervention strategy, which can help mitigate some of the potential workload increases associated with implementing the proposed Bill.">
