    <edge source="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee this morning. I have received apologies for absence from Jack Sargeant, and I'm very pleased to welcome Vikki Howells, who is substituting for Jack this morning. Can I ask whether there are any declarations of interest from Members, please? No. Okay. Thank you. Item 2 this morning is our last evidence session on the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill, and I'm really pleased to welcome back Julie Morgan AM, Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services; Karen Cornish, who is deputy director of the children and families division; and Emma Gammon, who is the lawyer working on the Bill. So, thank you all for coming. If you're happy, we'll go straight into questions because we've got lots of ground that we want to cover, and the first questions are from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Good morning. Thank you, Chair. Good morning, Deputy Minister. Of those individuals who responded to our written consultation in a personal capacity, nearly 70 per cent do not support this Bill" target="1. According to Sally Jenkins, a lead practitioner in children's services, there is not expected to be a significant increase in referrals related to the implementation of the Children's Bill. The threshold for intervention is also not anticipated to change significantly.&#10;2. Jane Randall from the National Independent Safeguarding Board shares this view and stated that she does not expect a huge increase in the number of referrals. She believes any potential rise can be managed within existing resources.&#10;3. While there might be an initial surge in reported incidents from individuals and organizations such as schools, social work professionals believe that awareness-raising campaigns and ongoing support for parents will lead to a decrease in physical punishment incidents over time.&#10;4. The British Association of Social Workers supports the legislation, but acknowledges the challenges faced by social workers who are already stretched and hard-pressed. They emphasize the importance of working closely with social services and collecting relevant data to establish a baseline and monitor changes after the Bill's implementation.&#10;5. Although there is no expectation of being overwhelmed, professionals acknowledge the need to be prepared for potential workload increases and monitor the situation closely. The Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service has expressed similar concerns but believes they have adequate resources to support the Bill's implementation.">
