    <edge source="The question is asking about confidence in the allocated budget of £2.2 million over six years for the organ donation awareness campaign, compared to previously spent amounts such as the £4 million for a similar campaign.&#10;&#10;Karen Cornish, the representative from the Welsh government, stated that they are &quot;as confident as we can be at this moment in time&quot; about the allocated budget being sufficient. However, she also mentioned working with focus groups and others to determine messaging needs, suggesting there may still be some uncertainty or ongoing planning efforts related to the campaign's budget.&#10;&#10;Lynne Neagle AM pointed out a disparity between the previously spent £4 million for an awareness campaign and the current allocation of £2.2 million over six years. She questioned whether this amount would be enough, especially considering that reaching various groups, including hard-to-reach ones, is necessary for such campaigns.&#10;&#10;Overall, while Karen Cornish expressed confidence in the allocated budget, there are concerns about whether it will be sufficient compared to previously spent amounts and taking into consideration the need to reach diverse audiences." target=" the evidence we've received. That's largely been recognised by the stakeholders who've given evidence, but isn't there still the potential for a degree of unknown costs to come into this, and what planning have you done for those unknown costs—those unforeseen costs—that might occur?&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: I feel that—. You're right that there always could be unknown costs, but we are doing our very best to prepare to cover all eventualities that we can anticipate. For example, I've committed to fund the high-intensity awareness-raising campaign, and committed to carry out a mapping exercise to establish whether there are any gaps in the parenting support. We know that evidence from other countries does show that, if we bring in this legislation and raise awareness, it does change people's attitudes, so there may, in the long term, be a saving if we do that. But we are committed to working with organisations to put in place arrangements so that we're able to collect the data so that we know what the impact is. But I just have to repeat that all our evidence, looking at other countries, is that there isn't a huge increase in the workload.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: No.">
