    <edge source="1. The purpose of the proposed Bill is to prohibit all forms of physical punishment against children, with the aim of protecting children's rights and ensuring that they have the same protection from physical punishment as adults. This change removes the legal defense for reasonable chastisement, which currently allows parents to use physical punishment as a form of discipline.&#10;2. According to a written consultation, nearly 70 percent of individuals who responded in a personal capacity do not support this Bill. Parents have expressed their understanding of the difference between child abuse and a light smack from a loving parent, indicating that they may perceive the proposed ban as an infringement on their ability to discipline their children." target="The text suggests that there is no expectation for the enactment of the Bill to lower the threshold for significant harm or change child protection procedures. The proposed legislation aims to prohibit all forms of physical punishment against children and ensure that they have the same protection from physical punishment as adults, removing the legal defense for reasonable chastisement. While there may be an initial surge in reported incidents, social services professionals believe that awareness-raising campaigns and ongoing support for parents will lead to a decrease in physical punishment incidents over time. The British Association of Social Workers supports the legislation but emphasizes the importance of working closely with social services and collecting relevant data to monitor changes after the Bill's implementation. Overall, while there may be potential workload increases, professionals are prepared and believe they have adequate resources to support the Bill's implementation without lowering the threshold for significant harm or changing child protection procedures significantly.">
