    <edge source="Based on the meeting transcript, it appears that teachers are expected to be prepared for the new legislation regarding parenting issues through various means. The implementation group, which includes representatives from the education sector, is tasked with preparing for the legislation's implementation and ensuring that professionals such as teachers are informed and ready. It is mentioned that teachers may undergo training as part of their in-service training days or courses to incorporate this new legislation into their knowledge and decision-making processes. The education sector's support for the move to ban physical punishment is also noted, implying a general readiness from teachers to adapt to the change. However, there is no explicit discussion about the extent of preparation or resources allocated specifically for teacher training in the transcript.&#10;&#10;It is important to note that while the education sector is represented in the implementation group, it does not necessarily mean that every individual teacher is prepared or involved in the process. The preparation and awareness campaign's success will likely depend on how effectively the information and training are cascaded down to all teachers and school staff. Additionally, there may be a transition period during which teachers become more comfortable with the new legislation and its implications for their professional responsibilities." target=" first meeting of the implementation group. So, they're going to be fully involved in the preparation. Obviously, corporal punishment was banned in schools a long time ago, and I think the education sector is very supportive of this move. But in terms of the awareness for teachers to be ready for it—obviously, the awareness campaign has got to be aimed at professionals in every field and certainly aimed at teachers.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: So, if I was a teacher in an individual school, what kind of preparation do you think I should expect?&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: You know this better than me, having been more in the education field than me, but I think teachers are updated on different parts of childcare legislation now, and have in-service training days and training courses. And, certainly, perhaps this would be part of that—part of the training that teachers get. This would have to be incorporated into that.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: One of the things that the National Association of Head Teachers told us was that they wouldn't want the cost of that kind of training to come from core budgets. Would you agree with that?&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content">
