    <edge source="1. The Welsh government has established an implementation group to address issues related to a proposed Bill that aims to prohibit physical punishment of children. This group had its first meeting on May 14th and includes representatives from various organizations such as the police, Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), Association of Directors of Social Services Cymru, Association of Directors of Education in Wales, Welsh Local Government Association, legal profession, and third sector.&#10;2. These organizations have expressed support for the principles of the Bill and are committed to making it work. They have set up four work streams to look at parenting advice and support, data collection, evaluation and monitoring, operations, procedures and processes, and out-of-court disposals and diversions.&#10;3. The implementation group's establishment is part of a broader early intervention strategy that involves investing in parenting programs and support services to mitigate potential workload increases associated with the Bill. No specific financial commitment has been provided upfront by the Welsh government, but they are relying on estimates and preparations made by the involved organizations.&#10;4. The Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services has stated that there is no expectation of significant increases in workload or negative impacts based on their understanding from people running these organizations. The organizations involved are already dealing with child protection and physical punishment issues, so it is not anticipated to be a completely new category of work for them.&#10;5. There have been concerns expressed about the rise in looked-after children and potential impacts on workload and resources for those working with them. There has also been a request for rough estimates of additional costs associated with implementing the Bill, as it could potentially lead to increased referrals and an increased workload for social services, family courts, CAFCASS Cymru, CPS, and organizations involved in child safeguarding." target=" that are taking part in the implementation group are, on the whole, in support of the principles of this Bill.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Well, thank you for that, Minister, but the way I look at this is that you've already said that, if this Bill passes—and it will pass; it's in enough manifestos to pass, so the question is what type of Bill is going to pass—and if there is a gap of, let's say, two years before anything is implemented, and the implementation group is doing the work that you've described—and we're very relieved to hear that—why is this Bill being introduced now when that implementation group hasn't really come up with a strategy that could help persuade people about what implementing this Bill would look like in real life? You're asking the Welsh public to take a bit of a chance on this.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: I think we have, as far as possible, looked at international evidence where this legislation has been introduced. It's different for different countries, so I know it's difficult to get anything that's absolutely linked. But I don't agree that it's a bit of a chance, really. I think we are preparing">
      <data key="d0">1</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="Julie Morgan AM, in response to the claim made by Equal Protection Network Cymru, asserts that the Bill aims to protect children's rights and ensure children have the same protection from physical punishment as adults. She acknowledges the varying views on this matter but emphasizes that the Wales Centre for Public Policy's independent literature review found all physical punishment under any conditions to be potentially harmful to children, with no peer-reviewed research suggesting physically punishing a child improves outcomes. While she understands Equal Protection Network Cymru's concerns, she maintains that the committee is reporting the evidence they received from their commissioned research." target=" So, there is other evidence, very widespread evidence, which looks at a whole range of people, that is in contrast to the Swedish evidence. But, evidence in this field is mixed and we have considered a wide range of research and reviews, but ultimately the decision is one that is based on our commitment to children's rights.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Do you want question 3?&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: I can do it, yes. The Bill's explanatory memorandum says that 'there is no definitive evidence that &quot;reasonable&quot; physical punishment causes negative outcomes for children'. However, we have heard from Equal Protection Network Cymru that international evidence could not be clearer and that they found the Wales Centre for Public Policy's report, on which the explanatory memorandum is based, very confusing and very frustrating, and that it didn't tie in with what they knew. How would you respond to those viewpoints?&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: We were very keen to get as balanced research as we possibly could, and we didn't want to just put forward views that we thought agreed with our point of view">
