    <edge source="Julie Morgan AM, in response to the claim made by Equal Protection Network Cymru, asserts that the Bill aims to protect children's rights and ensure children have the same protection from physical punishment as adults. She acknowledges the varying views on this matter but emphasizes that the Wales Centre for Public Policy's independent literature review found all physical punishment under any conditions to be potentially harmful to children, with no peer-reviewed research suggesting physically punishing a child improves outcomes. While she understands Equal Protection Network Cymru's concerns, she maintains that the committee is reporting the evidence they received from their commissioned research." target="1. Feasibility and process for providing a ballpark figure for an unforeseen fund: According to Julie Morgan AM, it is not feasible to provide a ballpark figure for an unforeseen fund at this time. She explains that they must measure the impact as they go along and rely on data to make predictions. This means that any costs related to the new legislation will be assessed and managed as the implementation progresses, rather than being able to provide a fixed estimate upfront.&#10;&#10;2. Relying on data to measure the impact of the legislation: Julie Morgan AM states that one of their sub-groups is specifically looking at data collection and analysis in relation to the new legislation. This sub-group will be responsible for gathering baseline data, measuring incidents after the implementation, and comparing the results to predict and understand the impact of the new law. They are particularly looking at New Zealand's experience with similar legislation, as it is one of the few countries that recorded incidents before and after bringing in the relevant legislation.">
