    <edge source="Julie Morgan AM, in response to the claim made by Equal Protection Network Cymru, asserts that the Bill aims to protect children's rights and ensure children have the same protection from physical punishment as adults. She acknowledges the varying views on this matter but emphasizes that the Wales Centre for Public Policy's independent literature review found all physical punishment under any conditions to be potentially harmful to children, with no peer-reviewed research suggesting physically punishing a child improves outcomes. While she understands Equal Protection Network Cymru's concerns, she maintains that the committee is reporting the evidence they received from their commissioned research." target="Julie Morgan AM's response to this claim would be that the Welsh Government commissioned a balanced and independent literature review from the Wales Centre for Public Policy to ensure a comprehensive understanding of the issue. According to their research, all physical punishment under any conditions is potentially harmful to children, with no peer-reviewed studies suggesting that physically punishing a child improves outcomes. While she understands Equal Protection Network Cymru's concerns, she maintains that the committee is reporting the evidence they received from their commissioned research.&#10;&#10;Julie Morgan AM also acknowledges that there is a range of international evidence on this subject, and while some of it indicates negative outcomes for children who experience 'reasonable' physical punishment, the Wales Centre for Public Policy report did not find this to be the case based on their assessment of available research. However, she recognizes that further awareness and understanding of the proposed legislation are needed, especially considering survey results indicating that over half of the population believes smacking is already illegal, suggesting a misunderstanding of the current law.">
