    <edge source="1. According to Sally Jenkins, a lead practitioner in children's services, there is not expected to be a significant increase in referrals related to the implementation of the Children's Bill. The threshold for intervention is also not anticipated to change significantly.&#10;2. Jane Randall from the National Independent Safeguarding Board shares this view and stated that she does not expect a huge increase in the number of referrals. She believes any potential rise can be managed within existing resources.&#10;3. While there might be an initial surge in reported incidents from individuals and organizations such as schools, social work professionals believe that awareness-raising campaigns and ongoing support for parents will lead to a decrease in physical punishment incidents over time.&#10;4. The British Association of Social Workers supports the legislation, but acknowledges the challenges faced by social workers who are already stretched and hard-pressed. They emphasize the importance of working closely with social services and collecting relevant data to establish a baseline and monitor changes after the Bill's implementation.&#10;5. Although there is no expectation of being overwhelmed, professionals acknowledge the need to be prepared for potential workload increases and monitor the situation closely. The Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service has expressed similar concerns but believes they have adequate resources to support the Bill's implementation." target="The Welsh Government is taking several measures to update the &quot;Parenting. Give it time&quot; campaign and improve support for parents, especially in the context of the proposed legislation to prohibit physical punishment of children. They have acknowledged the need for better awareness and understanding of the current law, as evidenced by a survey indicating that over half of the population believes smacking is already illegal. The Government is working on ensuring the public understands the proposed legislation as they move forward with it.&#10;&#10;In addition to updating the &quot;Parenting. Give it time&quot; campaign, which currently goes up to age 7 and focuses on issues like managing mealtime challenges and tantrums, the Welsh Government plans to extend its scope to cover up to 18 years old. This extension recognizes that the issues faced by parents of older children may be different and require tailored advice and support.&#10;&#10;The Government is also conducting a mapping exercise to identify gaps or opportunities for more support, particularly in terms of providing positive alternatives to physical punishment and online resources for parents. They recognize that many parents use various methods, including the internet, to access information and seek help. This mapping exercise will enable them to create targeted interventions and ensure comprehensive support is available for parents throughout Wales.&#10;&#10;Lastly, the Welsh Government encourages universal services provided by local government, health, education, social services, social justice, and the third sector to help support parents and pass on information about positive alternatives to physical punishment. More targeted supports such as Flying Start and Families First also offer help and advice for parents in need.">
